Construction of the Judicial Services Commission (JSC) composite building in Chinhoyi, in Zimbabwe nears completion after nearly 20 years of construction. The building will entail multiple courtrooms, offices, a library, a canteen and a kitchen. Also Read: First flagship UK government hub ‘Queen Elizabeth House’ completed Construction of the building began back in 2001 after the project was contracted to a Chinese firm with help from the Public Works Ministry. Construction works then stalled due to lack of funds. Works were then re-started in early 2018 after the new government assumed power. When fully complete, the single-storey building is expected to ease judicial officers and other ancillary staff accommodation woes.